Zachary Petersen

  Name
--------------------
MapGenerator

  Purpose
--------------------
Creates large images that can be used as backgrounds or ground planes in games.
These images are generated by placing tiles next to each other.
Simple examples of tiles could be: grass texture, dirt texture, etc.

	*each tile is stored as its own image
    
	-----                    -----            
    |*G*| <--- Grass Tile    | D | <--- Dirt Tile 
	-----                    -----             
	
	*large image is made by tiling instances of tile images next to each other.
	 In this example, an image depicting a dirt pathway through grass is created.
	
	----- ----- ----- ----- ----- -----
	| D | | D | |*G*| |*G*| |*G*| |*G*|
	----- ----- ----- ----- ----- -----
	----- ----- ----- ----- ----- -----
	|*G*| | D | |*G*| |*G*| |*G*| |*G*|
	----- ----- ----- ----- ----- -----    <--- Output Image
	----- ----- ----- ----- ----- -----
	|*G*| | D | | D | | D | |*G*| |*G*|
	----- ----- ----- ----- ----- -----
	----- ----- ----- ----- ----- -----
	|*G*| |*G*| |*G*| | D | |*G*| |*G*|
	----- ----- ----- ----- ----- -----
	

  Parameters
--------------------
Usage: python MapGenerator.py <inputImageName> <outputImageName> <templateFileName> <tileSize>

	--- <inputImageName>
	    Provide name (including file extension) of image that will be used to as a guide to generate 
		final output image. Each pixel on this image represents a tile on output image.
	
	--- <outPutImageName>
		Provide desired name of output image. DO NOT ADD FILE EXTENSION, output image will automatically
		be saved as a .png image.
		
	--- <templateFileName>
		Provide name of desired template file. (more information regarding template files below)
		
	--- <tileSize>
		Provide width or height of tile images that will be used. All tile images
		must be square, and all must have the same dimensions. EXAMPLE: if tile images are
		all 16px by 16px, this parameter must be '16'. Always must be an integer.
		
   Template Files
--------------------
Template files are used to map RGB values on the input image to Tiles. The template file itself is
a .txt file. Each line in the template file must be in this form:

	<redValue> <greenValue> <blueValue> <fileName>

For example, an actual line in a template file mile look like this
	
	150 27 255 ExampleTile.png
	
<redValue>, <greenValue>, and <blueValue> represent the RGB values (from 0 to 255) that will be mapped
to the corresponding image given by <fileName>.

   Exit Conditions
--------------------
0 = fine, 1 = illegal arguments, 2 = file not found (from argv), 3 = read error/file not found (from template file)